summary:
Acknowledges the contribution of the Regional Initiative, the South African facilitation, and other international partners to peace-building in Burundi and encourages them to remain engaged.

Reiterates its request for the Secretary-General, through BINUB, to play a robust political role in support of the peace process.

Decides that BINUB shall pay particular attention to supporting the electoral process, working in close cooperation with the Government of Burundi.
Here is a concise summary of the Security Council document:

The Security Council:

 Condemns none, but 
welcomes and  urges  various efforts on 
- democratic governance, peace consolidation, sustainable reintegration, and gender issues;

6. Urges the Burundian Government to create conditions for free, fair, and peaceful 2010 elections, and encourages dialogue through the Permanent Forum for Dialogue;

7. Urges the Government and political parties to preserve the independence and credibility of the Independent National Electoral Commission;

8. Supports a nationwide civic education campaign for the elections;

9. Requests BINUB to provide logistical support to the Electoral Commission if needed;

10. Requests the Executive Representative to facilitate dialogue among stakeholders;

11. Encourages the Government, Peacebuilding Commission, and partners to honour commitments under the Strategic Framework for Peacebuilding;

12. Encourages the Government to address peace consolidation challenges, including governance, security reforms, land tenure, justice, and human rights;

13. Encourages structural reforms to improve governance, with a focus on fighting corruption;

14. Urges international partners to support security sector reform;

15. Encourages completion of disarmament and demobilization and socio-economic reintegration;

16. Welcomes progress on durable solutions for refugees in Tanzania;

17. Encourages national consultations on transitional justice;

18. Calls for broadened respect and protection of human rights;

19. Expresses concern at continuing sexual and gender-based violence;

20. Welcomes the release of children by armed groups and emphasizes their sustainable reintegration;

21. Urges BINUB to strengthen cooperation with MONUC;

22. Requests a briefing on the electoral process and a report on BINUB's mandate implementation;

23. Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
